      <h2 class="m-b-3">What design systems do</h2>
    </div>
    <div class="cagov-mb-1">
      <p class="lead cagov-mb-3">They solve common problems digital teams commonly face. They combine UX principles, interface components, and code. Teams work faster, design better, and focus on new problems instead of old ones.</p>
      <div class="cagov-cluster-3">
        <span>
          <p class="cagov-bold">Make experiences consistent</p>
          <p>Services that use a design system feel familiar. This helps people trust a service, even if it's new to them.</p>
        </span>
        <span>
          <p class="cagov-bold">Build in accessibility and performance</p>
          <p>Components meet WCAG 2.1 accessibility standards. They work well across a range of devices and internet speeds.</p>
        </span>
      </div>
      <div class="cagov-cluster-3">
        <span>
          <p class="cagov-bold">Give tested solutions</p>
          <p>We test components before releasing them. This lets you deploy them with confidence.</p>
        </span>
        <span>
          <p class="cagov-bold">Speak a common language</p>
          <p>Shared names for components, patterns, and conventions increases collaboration within and across teams.</p>
        </span>
      </div>
      <div class="cagov-cluster-3">
        <span>
          <p class="cagov-bold">Leverage best practices</p>
          <p>Design systems capture tried-and-true best practices and allow other teams to use them.</p>
        </span>
        <span>
          <p class="cagov-bold">Use resources effectively</p>
          <p>With common problems already solved, teams can speed through the basics. You do more with less time and budget.</p>
        </span>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
